Luneon Libra, translated as Free Union, drew on the tradition of the blézón, a type of

41:51.880 --> 41:58.680
poem that celebrated the female body.

41:58.680 --> 41:59.680
So I'm going to read that.

41:59.680 --> 42:04.440
It's probably his most famous poem.

42:04.440 --> 42:10.720
My woman with her forest fire hair, with her heat lightning thoughts, with her hourglass

42:10.720 --> 42:17.440
waist, my woman with her otter waist in the tiger's mouth, my woman with her rosette

42:17.440 --> 42:24.160
mouth, the bouquet of stars of the brightest magnitude, with her teeth of white mouse footprints

42:24.160 --> 42:31.080
on the white earth, with her tongue of polished amber and glass, my woman with her stabbed

42:31.080 --> 42:38.440
eucharist tongue, with her tongue of a doll that opens and closes its eyes, with her tongue

42:38.440 --> 42:45.520
of incredible stone, my woman with her eyelashes in a child's handwriting, with her eyebrows

42:45.520 --> 42:52.040
the edge of a swallow's nest, my woman with her temples of a greenhouse with a slate roof

42:52.040 --> 42:58.800
and steam on the window panes, my woman with her shoulders of champagne and a dolphin-headed

42:58.800 --> 43:06.360
fountain under ice, my woman with her matchstick wrists, my woman with her lucky fingers, her

43:06.360 --> 43:13.240
ace of hearts' fingers, with her fingers of new mone hay, my woman with her armpits of

43:13.240 --> 43:21.120
martin and beach nuts, of midsummer night, of privet and angel fish nest, with her sea

43:21.120 --> 43:28.400
foam and floodgate arms, arms that mingle the wheat and the mill, my woman with rocket

43:28.400 --> 43:35.320
legs, with her movements of clockwork and despair, my woman with her calves of elder

43:35.320 --> 43:42.840
tree pith, my woman with her feet of initials, with her feet of bunches of keys, with her

43:42.840 --> 43:50.200
feet of weaver birds taking a drink, my woman with her pearl barley neck, my woman with

43:50.200 --> 43:57.800
her val door cleavage, cleavage of a rendezvous in the very bed of the mountain stream, with

43:57.800 --> 44:04.400
her breasts of night, my woman with her undersea molehill breasts, my woman with her breasts

44:04.400 --> 44:10.960
of the crucible of rubies, with her breasts of the spectre of the rose beneath the dew,

44:10.960 --> 44:18.880
my woman with her belly of the unfolding fan of days, with her giant claw belly, my woman

44:18.880 --> 44:25.040
with her back of a bird fleeing vertically, with her quick silver back, with her back

44:25.040 --> 44:32.200
of light, with her nape of rolled stone and damp chalk, and a glass and a falling glass

44:32.200 --> 44:39.200
that's just been sipped, my woman with her hips like a skiff, with her hips of a chandelier

44:39.200 --> 44:47.200
and arrow feathers, and stems of white peacock plumes, her hips, an imperceptible pair of

44:47.200 --> 44:54.200
scales, my woman with her buttocks of sandstone and asbestos, my woman with the buttocks of

44:54.200 --> 45:02.160
a swan's back, my woman with her buttocks of springtime, with her gladiolas, sex, my woman

45:02.160 --> 45:09.200
with her sex of place and platypus, my woman with her sex of seaweed and old-fashioned

45:09.200 --> 45:16.720
candies, my woman with her mirror sex, my woman with her eyes full of tears, with her

45:16.720 --> 45:24.720
eyes of violet armor and a speedometer needle, my woman with her savanna eyes, my woman with

45:24.720 --> 45:31.760
her eyes of water to drink in prison, my woman with her eyes of forests forever beneath the

45:31.760 --> 45:43.880
axe, with her eyes of sea level, air level, earth and fire.

45:43.880 --> 45:48.760
The surrealist who captured my heart, however, was Robert Desnos.

45:48.760 --> 45:54.760
Desnos was famous for his ability to speak poetry during the trance experiments that

45:54.760 --> 46:00.800
the group participated in for about a year, until some members of the group started to

46:00.800 --> 46:06.320
chase each other with knives, desnos among them.

46:06.320 --> 46:16.360
Here is one of Desnos' most beautiful poems from his poetic sequence called The Shadows,

46:16.360 --> 46:21.200
and this is called The Voice of Robert Desnos.

46:21.200 --> 46:26.200
So much like the flower and the current of air, like the waterway, like the shadows passing

46:26.200 --> 46:33.200
everywhere, like the smile glimpsed this amazing evening at midnight, so much like everything,

46:33.200 --> 46:35.440
happiness and sadness.

46:35.440 --> 46:41.760
It's yesterday's midnight lifting its naked torso above belfries and poplars.

46:41.760 --> 46:49.400
I'm calling those lost in the countryside, the old corpses, the young oaks just cut down,

46:49.400 --> 46:55.200
the shreds of fabric rotting on the ground and linen drying in farm yards.

46:55.200 --> 47:03.720
I'm calling tornadoes and hurricanes, tempests, typhoons and cyclones, riptides, earthquakes.

47:03.720 --> 47:11.160
I'm calling the smoke of volcanoes and cigarettes, the smoke rings of fancy cigars.

47:11.160 --> 47:13.920
I'm calling loves and lovers.

47:13.920 --> 47:16.720
I'm calling the living and the dead.

47:16.720 --> 47:18.200
I'm calling the grave diggers.

47:18.200 --> 47:20.000
I'm calling the murderers.

47:20.000 --> 47:26.080
I'm calling the executioners. I'm calling the pilots, the masons, the architects.

47:26.080 --> 47:27.880
I'm calling the flesh.

47:27.880 --> 47:30.200
I'm calling the one I love.

47:30.200 --> 47:32.920
I'm calling the one I love.

47:32.920 --> 47:36.720
I'm calling the one I love.

47:36.720 --> 47:42.720
Triumphant midnight unfolds its satin wings and lands on my bed.

47:42.720 --> 47:48.760
Suffries and poplars give into my desires.

47:48.760 --> 47:55.240
Those lost in the countryside find their bearings in finding me.

47:55.240 --> 47:58.960
The old corpses come back to life at my voice.

47:58.960 --> 48:03.520
The young oaks just cut down, wrapped themselves in greenery.

48:03.520 --> 48:08.920
The shreds of fabric rotting on the ground and on the ground, flap at my voice like the

48:08.920 --> 48:14.200
flag of rebellion. The linen drying in farm yards, clothes,

48:14.200 --> 48:21.800
adorable women that I don't adore, who come to me, obey my voice and adore me.

48:21.800 --> 48:24.680
The tornadoes spin around in my mouth.

48:24.680 --> 48:28.840
The hurricanes reden my lips if they can do it.

48:28.840 --> 48:31.560
The tempest snarl at my feet.

48:31.560 --> 48:35.520
The typhoons rumble my hair if they can do it.

48:35.520 --> 48:39.440
I accept the kisses of cyclone drunkenness.

48:39.440 --> 48:42.720
The riptides come to die at my feet.

48:42.720 --> 48:47.880
The earthquakes don't shake me but make everything totter at my command.

48:47.880 --> 48:54.600
The smoke of volcanoes attires me in its vapors, and cigarettes smoke perfumes me.

48:54.600 --> 48:58.480
And the smoke rings of fancy cigars crown me.

48:58.480 --> 49:03.960
The loved ones and the loved pursued for so long find shelter in me.

49:03.960 --> 49:06.200
The lovers hear my voice.

49:06.200 --> 49:09.120
The living and the dead give in and wave to me.

49:09.120 --> 49:13.200
The former, coolly, the latter intimately.

49:13.200 --> 49:18.680
The grave diggers abandon partly dug graves and announce that I am the only one who can

49:18.680 --> 49:21.320
direct their nighttime labors.

49:21.320 --> 49:23.360
The murderers greet me.

49:23.360 --> 49:26.360
The executioners invoke the revolution.

49:26.360 --> 49:28.200
Invoke my voice.

49:28.200 --> 49:30.200
Invoke my name.

49:30.200 --> 49:33.680
The pilots use my eyes to navigate.

49:33.680 --> 49:38.280
The masons are seized with vertigo, hearing me.

49:38.280 --> 49:40.960
The architects leave for the desert.

49:40.960 --> 49:42.880
The murderers bless me.

49:42.880 --> 49:46.320
The flesh quivers at my call.

49:46.320 --> 49:49.680
The one I love does not listen to me.

49:49.680 --> 49:53.160
The one I love does not hear me.

49:53.160 --> 49:57.560
The one I love does not answer me.

49:57.560 --> 50:11.000
Many of the surrealists fled to other countries during World War II, other stayed and worked

50:11.000 --> 50:16.960
for the resistance like Desnos and Paul El-Ward.

50:16.960 --> 50:21.960
Eventually Desnos was betrayed by a journalist.

50:21.960 --> 50:27.440
He died just after the liberation of Terezin, the ghetto and concentration camp in Czech

50:27.440 --> 50:30.600
oslovakia where he had been held prisoner.

50:30.600 --> 50:36.520
Two Czech students recognized him from the photographs that had appeared in Breton's

50:36.520 --> 50:42.640
book Naja and tried to help, but he was too ill with typhus to be saved.

50:42.640 --> 50:45.600
He was 45 years old.

50:45.600 --> 50:51.760
This is probably Desnos's best poem from a sequence of love poems called Ale Misterius,

50:51.760 --> 51:00.120
which I've translated as to the one of mystery.

51:00.120 --> 51:03.280
I've dreamed of you so much.

51:03.280 --> 51:08.240
I've dreamed of you so much you're losing your reality.

51:08.240 --> 51:14.360
Is there still time to reach that living body and kiss on that mouth the birth of the voice

51:14.360 --> 51:16.560
that's dear to me?

51:16.560 --> 51:22.080
I've dreamed of you so much that my arms used to crossing on my chest as I hugged your

51:22.080 --> 51:29.240
shadow couldn't fold themselves around the shape of your body, maybe.

51:29.240 --> 51:35.640
And faced with the actual appearance of what's haunted me and ruled me for days and years,

51:35.640 --> 51:39.680
I would probably turn into a shadow.

51:39.680 --> 51:44.000
Oh, what a sentimental pair of scales.

51:44.000 --> 51:49.320
I've dreamed of you so much there's probably no more time for me to wake up.

51:49.320 --> 51:56.520
I sleep standing up, my body exposed to all the appearances of life and love and you,

51:56.520 --> 52:00.880
the only thing that counts for me today.

52:00.880 --> 52:06.080
I'd probably reach for the first lips and face that came along, then your face and

52:06.080 --> 52:07.920
your lips.

52:07.920 --> 52:14.880
I've dreamed of you so much, walked so much, talked, slept with your phantom that maybe

52:14.880 --> 52:21.000
there's nothing left for me to do but be a phantom among the phantoms and a hundred

52:21.000 --> 52:27.880
times more shadow than the shadow that sturls and will go on strolling cheerfully over the

52:27.880 --> 52:34.480
sundial of your life.

52:34.480 --> 52:39.120
I am going on, aren't I, well, a couple more minutes.

52:39.120 --> 52:44.120
Breton whom the Nazis would have loved to lay their hands on fled to the United States

52:44.120 --> 52:50.160
and eked out a living as an officer, as an announcer for the office of war information.

52:50.160 --> 52:56.240
A friend of mine who worked alongside him told me that he refused to read any copy in which

52:56.240 --> 52:59.480
the pope was mentioned.

52:59.480 --> 53:04.600
Many other surrealists made it to the US as well, Max Ernst, Yves Tange, Kurt Seligman,

53:04.600 --> 53:07.000
and Andre Masson among them.

53:07.000 --> 53:12.200
And as they made their way into the American art scene and its society, their influence

53:12.200 --> 53:18.800
left behind the beginnings of the New York School of Painting that included Robert Motherwell,

53:18.800 --> 53:26.160
Jackson Pollock, Arshil Gorky, Milton Avery among others, which in turn had a marked influence

53:26.160 --> 53:34.240
on poets like Frank O'Hara, John Ashbury, Kenneth Koch, Barbara Guest, and James Schuyler.

53:34.240 --> 53:39.040
They became known as the New York School of Poetry, a group that has written its own

53:39.040 --> 53:42.600
chapter in our recent literary history.

53:42.600 --> 53:47.760
These were, and are, Ashbury is still very much alive, poets who were deeply influenced

53:47.760 --> 53:52.280
by French literary and artistic surrealism.

53:52.280 --> 53:58.880
In the 20s, surrealism spread throughout Europe, inspiring groups in Belgium, Eastern Europe,

53:58.880 --> 54:03.000
Mexico, to which Benjamin Parre had immigrated.

54:03.000 --> 54:09.160
Martinique Spain, Breton lectured in Barcelona two years before he published his manifesto

54:09.160 --> 54:12.360
of surrealism in 1924.

54:12.360 --> 54:16.360
Latin America, Egypt, and even Japan.

54:16.360 --> 54:21.800
English translations of surrealist writings began to appear in American and British literary

54:21.800 --> 54:28.880
magazines in the 20s, and by the late 50s Robert Bly the poet was beating the drum for

54:28.880 --> 54:35.160
a poetry of the unconscious, though ultimately he repudiated French surrealism in favor of

54:35.160 --> 54:41.800
Spanish language surrealism, Lorka, Neruda, Bayejo, and others.

54:41.800 --> 54:48.720
The 60s and 70s saw the creation of a Chicago group of surrealists led by Franklin Rosemont

54:48.720 --> 54:53.360
and his wife Penelope, to me their efforts seemed to be a rehash of work that the French

54:53.360 --> 54:55.280
had done.

54:55.280 --> 55:02.320
Right now there is some discussion, particularly among certain West Coast poets, of a neo-surrealism.

55:02.320 --> 55:08.920
At 16, the San Francisco poet Philip La Montia had come to New York, showed his poems to

55:08.920 --> 55:15.360
Breton, and been given a job at V.V.V.V. or V.V.V.A., a surrealist magazine published

55:15.360 --> 55:18.480
during Breton's New York years.

55:18.480 --> 55:24.760
This is a voice that rises once in 100 years, Breton said of La Montia.

55:24.760 --> 55:30.600
But La Montia published very little, and a promising surrealist poet named Pete Winslow,

55:30.600 --> 55:38.760
also based in San Francisco, died in his 30s of complications following surgery.

55:38.760 --> 55:43.560
Surrealism however had a tremendous impact on the poets of the beat generation, most notably

55:43.560 --> 55:51.080
on Alan Ginsburg, and there is a legion of beat-derived surrealists all over the planet.

55:51.080 --> 55:56.680
I wish I could tell you what neo-surrealism is, and who is in it, but it seems to include

55:56.680 --> 55:58.400
everyone.

55:58.400 --> 56:00.280
This is no surprise.

56:00.280 --> 56:07.520
In his third surrealist manifesto, written after Breton had thrown him out of the group,

56:07.520 --> 56:10.760
Robert Desnos put it this way.

56:10.760 --> 56:19.160
For surrealists, there is only one reality, complete, open to everyone.

56:19.160 --> 56:24.200
Surrealism has fallen into the public domain.

56:24.200 --> 56:29.680
Surrealist practice in poetry has made its way into American poetry for well over 80 years

56:29.680 --> 56:31.240
now.

56:31.240 --> 56:35.480
When everyone is a surrealist, no one has to be a surrealist.

56:35.480 --> 56:40.760
There are precious few groups to join, and no manifestos to sign.

56:40.760 --> 56:48.480
Poets can partake of the enormous gifts bequeathed in writing, and in all the arts by the surrealists,

56:48.480 --> 56:51.400
and that's good enough for me.

56:51.400 --> 56:52.400
Thank you.

56:52.400 --> 56:53.400
Thank you.

56:53.400 --> 56:59.440
Well, do you have no, I'll ask this question later.

56:59.440 --> 57:04.080
Does anyone have a handful of things they'd like to add to things that they've heard,

57:04.080 --> 57:07.960
or questions they'd like to answer, or like answered?

57:07.960 --> 57:08.960
No?

57:08.960 --> 57:15.200
I would too, but we have a little extra time.

57:15.200 --> 57:16.520
I was going to ask the audience.

57:16.520 --> 57:21.600
I will ask the audience, but in the meantime, I thought, well, we still have the stage.

57:21.600 --> 57:26.520
Does anyone have anything to add or question about all this?

57:26.520 --> 57:27.520
No?

57:27.520 --> 57:28.520
I think it's interesting.

57:28.520 --> 57:29.520
Bill Sutter.

57:29.520 --> 57:36.800
We've only just read four poems out of 20,000.

57:36.800 --> 57:46.640
It's daunting to try to make such a selection, but go out there and get the books.

57:46.640 --> 57:49.080
That's an idea.

57:49.080 --> 57:50.080
Yeah.

57:50.080 --> 57:54.920
There are a lot of translations out there that are well worth reading, Mary Ann's.

57:54.920 --> 57:59.680
And there's a list outside.

57:59.680 --> 58:05.080
I think the point is, we can only possibly touch on a very small piece of it, which is

58:05.080 --> 58:06.080
what we've done today.

58:06.080 --> 58:10.040
We've looked at the poetry, we've touched a little about the psychoanalysis, we've touched

58:10.040 --> 58:15.880
a tiny bit on the art, but surrealism has so many other aspects that we can't possibly

58:15.880 --> 58:16.880
talk about.

58:16.880 --> 58:17.880
It's very big.

58:17.880 --> 58:18.880
Very, very big.

58:18.880 --> 58:20.680
And it's several of us have mentioned.

58:20.680 --> 58:24.840
It's now diffused itself into the current of everyday life, to the point where it means

58:24.840 --> 58:28.480
everything and nothing, but it still has a particular meaning.

58:28.480 --> 58:36.040
And it still has a corpus of writings that remain relevant and oddly enough, translate

58:36.040 --> 58:40.120
in a number of cases very well, although that's something you wouldn't think would be possible

58:40.120 --> 58:41.120
for automatic writing.

58:41.120 --> 58:46.360
I mean, I guess if I have a question, I would direct it to the two eminent surrealist translators

58:46.360 --> 58:48.360
sitting right here in front of me, which is...

58:48.360 --> 58:52.000
I can argue with...one argument is the my woman.

58:52.000 --> 58:55.960
Of course, my woman brought on my farm.

58:55.960 --> 58:58.760
So we, others have translated it differently.

58:58.760 --> 59:01.840
I translated it as my beloved, so I don't go into the problem.

59:01.840 --> 59:06.000
You can't say my wife, because it was done for three different people at different times,

59:06.000 --> 59:07.760
so forget my wife.

59:07.760 --> 59:10.000
And my woman just gets right in my nerves.

59:10.000 --> 59:16.560
So I took it out of the random house of French poetry, because I didn't think my woman could

59:16.560 --> 59:17.560
work for it.

59:17.560 --> 59:27.600
I think it's interesting that I suppose it's the interwar poetry, the poetry between the

59:27.600 --> 59:29.400
First World War and the Second World War.

59:29.400 --> 59:31.800
It's so full of love poems.

59:31.800 --> 59:38.600
I mean, rather amazing for a huge movement like that, or maybe it's because it was so

59:38.600 --> 59:47.440
particularly French, but it is amazingly full of love and real love, not just love poems.

59:47.440 --> 59:48.440
And also, yeah, go ahead.

59:48.440 --> 59:50.720
No, I was just going to say I think it's full of two things.

59:50.720 --> 59:52.720
It's full of love, but it's also full of despair.

59:52.720 --> 59:56.080
I mean, I think as we listen to the poems that were read here tonight, there's this,

59:56.080 --> 59:57.080
you know, I think you mentioned that.

59:57.080 --> 59:59.080
There's this core of real desperation.

59:59.080 --> 01:00:00.840
She does an answer on calling out.

01:00:00.840 --> 01:00:05.760
There's, you know, no matter what it is, even there's very little happy love and surrealism.

01:00:05.760 --> 01:00:10.920
I think that there was a huge...love was valued above everything else.

01:00:10.920 --> 01:00:17.360
I mean, it was sort of the core driver, the core emotion, but it never seems to work

01:00:17.360 --> 01:00:18.360
out very well.

01:00:18.360 --> 01:00:19.360
Well, does it?

01:00:19.360 --> 01:00:20.360
I mean...

01:00:20.360 --> 01:00:21.360
Sometimes it happens.

01:00:21.360 --> 01:00:27.560
It seems to work out fairly well for Desmos, who had a lot of disappointments and wrote

01:00:27.560 --> 01:00:35.080
a lot of great poems about his disappointments, but he married and seemed to have very good

01:00:35.080 --> 01:00:36.320
marriage.

01:00:36.320 --> 01:00:42.240
And there's a heartbreaking letter that he wrote from...I don't know if it was from

01:00:42.240 --> 01:00:48.800
Terezin or from Compiène or...

01:00:48.800 --> 01:00:50.080
And d'Ronsie, yeah.

01:00:50.080 --> 01:00:54.520
And it's just this heartbreaking letter about how everything's going to...you know, did

01:00:54.520 --> 01:00:55.520
you get the package?

01:00:55.520 --> 01:00:59.920
I sent you...I got your package and so forth and so on.

01:00:59.920 --> 01:01:03.720
What about my book that's in press now?

01:01:03.720 --> 01:01:08.040
And you know, I promise you that we're going to have a wonderful life when we are able

01:01:08.040 --> 01:01:10.080
to get back together again.

01:01:10.080 --> 01:01:15.280
And it just breaks your heart, but that was a beautiful romance.

01:01:15.280 --> 01:01:20.360
Well, love is always full of love and despair.

01:01:20.360 --> 01:01:24.440
I mean, that's not unusual.

01:01:24.440 --> 01:01:30.240
It's just that as subject matter, so much of the subject matter.

01:01:30.240 --> 01:01:34.400
Also I think it's interesting that in a way it is so cheerful.

01:01:34.400 --> 01:01:36.240
It is also up.

01:01:36.240 --> 01:01:40.040
It has an up spirit to it, regardless of what it says.

01:01:40.040 --> 01:01:45.440
But it is optimistic, and that's perhaps the political situation that to begin with people

01:01:45.440 --> 01:01:47.640
were optimistic after the first world war.

01:01:47.640 --> 01:01:50.680
I suppose it didn't last long.

01:01:50.680 --> 01:01:56.840
And there's something that makes us all laugh still when we hear some of these things.

01:01:56.840 --> 01:02:03.040
And of course it's penetrated so deeply into society that we don't think of the stuff we

01:02:03.040 --> 01:02:05.000
do as a surrealist.

01:02:05.000 --> 01:02:12.320
But as an abstract painter, I sort of now realize surrealism has been part of the landscape

01:02:12.320 --> 01:02:14.160
in my head since I was a child.

01:02:14.160 --> 01:02:21.120
If not for surrealism and my paintings are not surrealist, none of this would happen.

01:02:21.120 --> 01:02:22.120
It gave permission.

01:02:22.120 --> 01:02:23.640
And it gives a great freedom.

01:02:23.640 --> 01:02:25.120
It gives you freedom.

01:02:25.120 --> 01:02:26.120
Yeah, complete freedom.

01:02:26.120 --> 01:02:27.120
Yeah.

01:02:27.120 --> 01:02:28.120
Which is a question my point.

01:02:28.120 --> 01:02:33.320
Well, do you think also later on thinking of the beast now, you know, Kerouac discovered

01:02:33.320 --> 01:02:37.760
what he called spontaneous boprocity.

