01:07:32.640 --> 01:07:36.880
Because Bertone was somebody who, you know, brilliant as he was, as creative a mind as

01:07:36.880 --> 01:07:42.840
he was, was kind of known for taking bits and pieces of the work that he read and then

01:07:42.840 --> 01:07:43.840
running with it.

01:07:43.840 --> 01:07:44.840
This was the case with Freud.

01:07:44.840 --> 01:07:48.760
This was the case with Hegel, who he also claimed as a great formation, as a case with

01:07:48.760 --> 01:07:49.760
Marx.

01:07:49.760 --> 01:07:55.800
But if you actually look what Bertone wrote about Freud, Hegel and Marx, it's not a deep

01:07:55.800 --> 01:07:56.800
analysis.

01:07:56.800 --> 01:08:00.960
It's picking and choosing the bits and pieces that can serve his own purpose.

01:08:00.960 --> 01:08:04.840
His use of Freud was really fairly superficial when you get down to it.

01:08:04.840 --> 01:08:07.040
You know, Bertone was not a great Freudian scholar.

01:08:07.040 --> 01:08:12.960
He was someone who had been deeply excited by the discovery of Freud's early theories

01:08:12.960 --> 01:08:20.400
and especially his work with dreams and with the automatic states, which was also came,

01:08:20.400 --> 01:08:28.200
which also came from, you know, some of the other early psychoanalysts, but Freud in particular.

01:08:28.200 --> 01:08:35.200
And I don't know that his use and analysis of psychoanalysis went so far as to penetrate

01:08:35.200 --> 01:08:37.760
into variant forms or the other people.

01:08:37.760 --> 01:08:40.400
You know, really Freud was sort of where his focus was.

01:08:40.400 --> 01:08:44.760
And because it was where his focus was, it tended to be where the other surrealist focus

01:08:44.760 --> 01:08:45.760
was.

01:08:45.760 --> 01:08:50.840
Jung is a name that comes in, I can't really even think of time-sitting.

01:08:50.840 --> 01:08:52.320
Thank you, Bertone.

