But again, those weren't available until the last few years.

01:10:32.200 --> 01:10:33.200
Yeah.

01:10:33.200 --> 01:10:38.920
Again, thank you so much for your good words and your passion for this.

01:10:38.920 --> 01:10:41.440
I have a question that's more about present day.

01:10:41.440 --> 01:10:45.440
If like Breton was sitting in the chair right now and he could be present and say, well,

01:10:45.440 --> 01:10:47.400
what does this mean today?

01:10:47.400 --> 01:10:53.480
I'd like to just ask you, I'm very much taken by the nature of like, what is imagination?

01:10:53.480 --> 01:11:00.240
They were like Breton, a higher level of consciousness exploring human potentiality, creation, meaning.

01:11:00.240 --> 01:11:06.760
So when imagination, some people say it's a more holistic, creative, open-ended, your

01:11:06.760 --> 01:11:08.840
brain is creating your imagination.

01:11:08.840 --> 01:11:10.480
Where else could it come from?

01:11:10.480 --> 01:11:11.480
But it's holistic.

01:11:11.480 --> 01:11:12.480
It has a sense of innate beauty.

01:11:12.480 --> 01:11:13.480
You share it.

01:11:13.480 --> 01:11:14.480
You include it.

01:11:14.480 --> 01:11:18.400
North of Fry, one of the few people wrote a book about it, said, imagination creates

01:11:18.400 --> 01:11:23.840
a bridge that allows emotion and intelligence to form together to create meaning.

01:11:23.840 --> 01:11:28.800
So I was wondering with all the background that you have of how would you understand

01:11:28.800 --> 01:11:34.240
or explain what is imagination as a form of consciousness?

01:11:34.240 --> 01:11:38.360
And is there any way that you can imagine we can create some understanding to promote

01:11:38.360 --> 01:11:45.960
those better ideas to get out of the locked up thinking which eliminates emotion which

01:11:45.960 --> 01:11:48.120
you cannot create meaning without?

01:11:48.120 --> 01:11:52.360
I'm just throwing it out to you, whatever you can come up with, I'd appreciate it.

01:11:52.360 --> 01:11:54.360
That's a hard one.

01:11:54.360 --> 01:11:55.360
Next time.

01:11:55.360 --> 01:11:57.360
Does anyone have any of these?

01:11:57.360 --> 01:12:02.960
It's a vast subject.

01:12:02.960 --> 01:12:08.640
In terms of just to hark back to the idea of the metaphor, Pierre Revardis, one of the

01:12:08.640 --> 01:12:15.480
great 20th century French poets and a kind of a mentor to Breton at least intellectually,

01:12:15.480 --> 01:12:22.560
he said, the metaphor flies in on its own wings.

01:12:22.560 --> 01:12:28.480
And Breton has great pains to point out, you can't sit down and think up a really good

01:12:28.480 --> 01:12:30.360
metaphor.

01:12:30.360 --> 01:12:32.600
It either comes or it doesn't.

01:12:32.600 --> 01:12:40.120
And in fact, you can go back and read Aristotle and this idea is right there in Aristotle.

01:12:40.120 --> 01:12:46.080
So it's a vast subject and a great one.

01:12:46.080 --> 01:12:50.040
And what is the imagination?

01:12:50.040 --> 01:12:52.000
And I think there have been a number of answers to it.

01:12:52.000 --> 01:12:59.800
But in the surrealist case, I think for one thing, Breton was a pure product of French,

01:12:59.800 --> 01:13:01.360
bourgeois, rationalist society.

01:13:01.360 --> 01:13:04.600
And that was the enemy that he fought against his entire life.

01:13:04.600 --> 01:13:06.600
Was Greco-Roman logic.

01:13:06.600 --> 01:13:08.560
That was the main target.

01:13:08.560 --> 01:13:14.760
And so the entire enterprise of surrealism, whether through its brief flirtation of interest

01:13:14.760 --> 01:13:21.800
and Buddhism through Toronto or psychoanalysis or whatever it might be, was to allow the

01:13:21.800 --> 01:13:27.800
conditions, create the conditions for which you could open your mind to the flood of images

01:13:27.800 --> 01:13:33.640
that would come in and not constantly try to filter or not constantly try to eliminate

01:13:33.640 --> 01:13:37.200
the ones that didn't make sense or the ones that didn't seem to conform to some arbitrary

01:13:37.200 --> 01:13:42.640
rule of what images should be, that all of it was valid and all of it was useful.

01:13:42.640 --> 01:13:50.560
It's a curious thing because surrealism itself as an entity, as a movement, was actually

01:13:50.560 --> 01:13:52.080
heavily regulated.

01:13:52.080 --> 01:13:57.160
Breton himself was a great theorist of the liberty of thought, the freedom of thought

01:13:57.160 --> 01:13:59.400
and at the same time was enormously controlled.

01:13:59.400 --> 01:14:01.640
He was a real control freak.

01:14:01.640 --> 01:14:07.920
And so there's a, in a way you can almost say it's the tension between the two that

01:14:07.920 --> 01:14:12.320
actually produced that spark that allowed surrealism to last as an active movement for

01:14:12.320 --> 01:14:14.480
something like 50 years.

01:14:14.480 --> 01:14:20.200
And it was interesting and probably not that surprising that shortly after his death in

01:14:20.200 --> 01:14:26.960
1966, his hand-picked successor, who was in every way as forceful and dynamic as Breton

01:14:26.960 --> 01:14:31.360
was, a man named Josh Eustaire, tried to keep the movement going.

01:14:31.360 --> 01:14:36.240
And there were two things, curiously enough, that finally put an end to it three years

01:14:36.240 --> 01:14:37.800
later in 1969.

01:14:37.800 --> 01:14:43.360
One of them was the May 68 riots because the surrealists felt that it had actually gotten

01:14:43.360 --> 01:14:50.840
out of there, it had passed them by, that the students were using surrealist ideas and

01:14:50.840 --> 01:14:55.000
putting, scrolling surrealist slogans on the walls and they felt that this thing that

01:14:55.000 --> 01:14:57.960
we've created has now just completely steamrolled over us.

01:14:57.960 --> 01:15:00.400
We have no further place in it.

01:15:00.400 --> 01:15:01.400
That was one.

01:15:01.400 --> 01:15:06.600
And the other one was the fact that Schuistaire realized that without Breton there as a kind

01:15:06.600 --> 01:15:11.320
of a force, just a personal force that could hold all the little factions together in that

01:15:11.320 --> 01:15:13.240
group, it just fell apart.

01:15:13.240 --> 01:15:15.280
There was no one there who could keep it going anymore.

01:15:15.280 --> 01:15:17.760
There was no one there who had the force of personality.

01:15:17.760 --> 01:15:25.040
So on the one hand, you've got this wonderful call to freedom and to the primacy of love

01:15:25.040 --> 01:15:35.920
and absolute imagination sort of cemented against or sort of laminated to this other

01:15:35.920 --> 01:15:40.080
need and will toward real regulation.

01:15:40.080 --> 01:15:43.040
And oddly enough, that was the energy that kept it going.

01:15:43.040 --> 01:15:49.640
You will have one statement of Breton, the imaginary tends to become the real kind of

01:15:49.640 --> 01:15:50.640
wonderful.

01:15:50.640 --> 01:15:55.480
I just thought you brought up in 3,000 years ago where there is no vision the people will

01:15:55.480 --> 01:15:56.480
perish.

01:15:56.480 --> 01:15:58.240
And Jung said image is everything.

01:15:58.240 --> 01:16:02.760
I mean, human potentiality is presented in the form of an image or word is just a name

01:16:02.760 --> 01:16:04.920
for an object, it doesn't mean anything.

01:16:04.920 --> 01:16:09.040
But Jung said, and might unfortunately take 600 years for the rest of the world to catch

01:16:09.040 --> 01:16:10.040
on.

01:16:10.040 --> 01:16:11.040
So thank you.

01:16:11.040 --> 01:16:12.040
Thank you.

01:16:12.040 --> 01:16:15.640
Well, I was also very glad to hear all of this.

01:16:15.640 --> 01:16:18.720
I'm a painter and also art historian.

01:16:18.720 --> 01:16:22.920
And I've been interested in the subject for a long time, starting with the symbolist with

01:16:22.920 --> 01:16:25.760
Bodleaire and Rambo and Malarmé.

01:16:25.760 --> 01:16:31.320
And I'm very interested in the relationship to the painters because earlier on, but even

01:16:31.320 --> 01:16:38.440
later, Bonard and Braque and Matisse were very allied with the poets.

01:16:38.440 --> 01:16:46.040
There is no particularly with Braque and Robert D. And Matisse even began to speak about his

01:16:46.040 --> 01:16:47.600
world of signs.

01:16:47.600 --> 01:16:53.800
And what I'd like to ask is did the poets use this word signs or was it more from the

01:16:53.800 --> 01:16:59.640
phenomenologists and Bachellard and the philosophers of France that brought up the concept of

01:16:59.640 --> 01:17:00.640
signs?

01:17:00.640 --> 01:17:02.800
Or does it go back to Bodleaire?

01:17:02.800 --> 01:17:08.040
Because Matisse, particularly now that his cutout show is there, you can see how he

01:17:08.040 --> 01:17:12.760
transpose this concept of signs into visual signs.

